# Bandit Level 10 → Level 11

## Objective
The goal of this level was to find the password for the next level.  
The password was stored in the file `data.txt`, which contained Base64 encoded data.

---

## Challenge
At first, I thought this level was very straightforward because the challenge clearly mentioned Base64 encoding.

I initially used:

base64 data.txt

This returned encoded-looking text:

VkdobElIQmhjM04zYjNKa0lHbHpJR1IwVWpFM00yWmFTMkl3VWxKelJFWlRSM05uTWxKWGJuQk9W
bW96Y1ZKeUNnPT0K

However, I realised this was not the actual password. After doing some research, I learned that the `base64` command by itself encodes data rather than decoding it.

I then discovered that the `-d` option is required to decode Base64 data.

---

## Steps I Took

I used the following command:

base64 -d data.txt

The `-d` option decoded the contents of the file and displayed the password for the next level.

---

## Password for Level 11
dtR173fZKb0RRsDFSGsg2RWnpNVj3qRr

---

## Commands Learned

### base64
The `base64` command is used to encode and decode Base64 data.

### -d
The `-d` option tells the command to decode the data instead of encoding it.

### base64 -d data.txt
This command decoded the Base64 encoded contents of `data.txt` and revealed the password.
